tweet: So, IMO, you might as well pass the bill to help farmers and also create a USDA certification process that will give us more confidence that the carbon offsets represent real carbon sequestration. Right now too many offsets are vaporware. The more oversight, the better.
name: Dana Nuccitelli

tweet: The reason the bill has bipartisan support is that it just connects farmers to existing carbon offset market revenue streams. Cheap, simple solution. Another key point: carbon offset markets will continue to grow with or without the Growing Climate Solutions Act.
name: Dana Nuccitelli

tweet: But other climate groups endorse the bill because it will help farmers get funding to move to regenerative agricultural practices, which have the potential to be a significant climate solution, sequestering carbon in soils.
name: Dana Nuccitelli

tweet: I also touched on a bipartisan(!) climate bill called the Growing Climate Solutions Act, that would help connect farmers/ranchers/private forest owners to carbon offset markets. Many of the same groups oppose it for similar reasons: offsets allow polluters to keep polluting.
name: Dana Nuccitelli
